bug.short_desc: qx.ui.container.SlideBar prevents page scrolling with mouse wheel

long_desc.thetext: The qx.ui.container.SlideBar widget is blocking mousewheel events from reaching its container, which prevents the page from being scrolled with the mouse wheel. See attached playground snippet for a demo.

Ok, here's the problem. The SlideBar class doesn't know whether the mouse wheel was rotated, or whether it was pressed side-to-side. On a horizontal SlideBar, a wheel rotation gives a delta of zero when calling e.getWheelDelta("x"), which is perfectly correct, because there was no side-to-side press of the mouse wheel. That, however, must not cause e.stop() to be called. That wheel rotation needs to be sent through to the parent, so that the application can scroll.
By adding this extra method, the receiver of the event (SlideBar) can determine whether the mouse wheel was rotated or whether it was pressed side-to-side, and ignore processing the event if it was rotated over a horizontal SlideBar, or pressed side-to-side over a vertical SlideBar.
> Could you maybe tell me what didn't work for you and on which browser?
Yes. I'm using Firefox 5.0 and Chrome 12.0.742.100 on Linux.
What didn't work is that rotating the mouse wheel over a SlideBar did not scroll the application vertically. In fact, rotating the mouse wheel over a SlideBar caused absolutely no reaction. This is true with or without your initial fix.
Hope that helps.
Derrell

I just had a thought...
If we are GUARANTEED that a delta of zero means that it was the "other" axis (not the one requested in the parameter to getWheelDelta()) that caused the event, then we could eliminate the getAxis() method I added, and the user (SlideBar) could ignore the event if delta was zero.
Derrell

The problem is not that easy because imagine using a touchpad where you can scroll in both directions at the same time. So its just not a good idea to offer a method which pretends that this is not possible. Thats why I would remove this method. Instead, we should trust the data from the event and take it as it is. If the scrolling is delate 0, there has been no scrolling action in that direction.
I checked if and found a easy solution by just not stopping the event if the delta is 0. That way, it should work (checked it on chrome and ff with both, a touchpad and such a mouse you described)
Therefore, I reverted your commit which added the new method.
